@kaiw , @johannes_p 

Hi guys! I refactored the CVS module, according to the new vc API. Actually I  tried to implement what I've seen in the Mercurial module.

I've found a way to avoid reverse patching and to avoid digging into the files like CVS/Entries. So I hope, Meld will do it for the few of us who use CVS. See the MR !35

From what I can tell, "en_US_POSIX" has been the official name of the locale for a long time (maybe forever), so it should not cause problems with older versions (I don't have the means to test it, though).  Looking a little closer at the ICU source code, it seems that just switching the names might not be as robust as their old system, since they process the input locale quite a bit before doing the mapping.  The main reason I suggest trying to maintain the behavior is that it looks like evolution-data-server takes the system locale (which might be "POSIX" or "C") and passes it directly to ICU.  I may have misread the code, though.

ICU has a utility function called "uprv_getPOSIXIDForCategory", which is essentially a wrapper for `setlocale(x, NULL)`.  It has the following check:

```
if ((posixID==0)
    || (uprv_strcmp("C", posixID) == 0)
    || (uprv_strcmp("POSIX", posixID) == 0))
{
    /* Nothing worked.  Give it a nice POSIX default value. */
    posixID = "en_US_POSIX";
}
```
Replacing "setlocale" with that wrapper seems like a pretty big and complicated change.  Putting a similar check in "canonicalize_locale" would probably be a good work-around.

Also, it looks like other people are having problems with this change: <https://unicode-org.atlassian.net/browse/ICU-20575>.  It may get partially reverted.

